SIMPLE: trot
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trot
<hw>Trot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trotted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trotting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>trotten</ets>, OF.
<ets>troter</ets>, F. <ets>trotter</ets>; probably of Teutonic origin,
and akin to E. <ets>tread</ets>; cf. OHG. <ets>trott<?/n</ets> to tread.
See <er>Tread</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To proceed by a certain gait
peculiar to quadrupeds; to ride or drive at a trot. See <er>Trot</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To run; to jog; to hurry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that rises late must <qex>trot</qex> all day, and will scarcely
overtake his business at night.</q> <rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trot
<hw>Trot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to move, as a horse or
other animal, in the pace called a trot; to cause to run without
galloping or cantering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To trot out</b></col>, <cd>to lead or bring out, as a
horse, to show his paces; hence, to bring forward, as for
exhibition.</cd> <mark>[Slang.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trot
<hw>Trot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Trot</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The pace of a horse or other quadruped,
more rapid than a walk, but of various degrees of swiftness, in which
one fore foot and the hind foot of the opposite side are lifted at the
same time.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The limbs move diagonally in pairs in the
<xex>trot</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Stillman (The Horse in
Motion).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: A jogging pace, as of a person
hurrying.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who trots; a child; a woman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An old <qex>trot</qex> with ne'er a tooth.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troth</ent>⟦br⟧
